Midnight raids on welfare recipients continued for most of the 1960s. 27 During that time, a number of publicized cases of welfare fraud charges resulted from the raids.2 8 In many of those cases, though, the men, not the women, were charged with fraud. Men found residing with women receiving welfare aid were treated as the welfare cheats.29 The prosecutions of men, rather than women, suggest that the welfare and law enforcement officials considered women to be easily manipulated by the men, but ultimately blameless in the cheating. This view of the innocence of women, however, changed over time.
